# Phase 2 — Engineering Practice Analysis

Findings below are grouped by category, with the specific evidence I
found in the codebase for each one.

## Architecture & API Design

✅ **Good — Business logic is written as pure functions.**
`computeKPIs()` and `computeMonthlyData()` in `financial-utils.ts` just
take data in and return data out — no fetching, no rendering, no
side effects. That's what makes them easy to unit test (there's a
`financial-utils.test.ts` for exactly that reason), unlike the visual
components, which have no tests at all.

⚠️ **Risky — Most of the backend's capability is unused.**
`routes.py` defines 9 endpoints with filtering by date, category,
operation type, and business type. The frontend only calls one of
them — `/api/metrics`, with no query params at all. Confirmed with
`grep -rn "fetch(" .` in `frontend/src`: one match, total. That's a
lot of backend logic that looks functional but has never actually been
exercised by the app.

## Data Contracts & Type Safety

✅ **Good — Inputs are constrained with `Literal` types instead of plain strings.**
`OperationType`, `Category`, `BusinessType`, and `GroupBy` (`routes.py`,
lines 11–14) are all typed as fixed sets of allowed values. FastAPI
validates these automatically before the request even reaches business
logic — bad input gets rejected at the door instead of causing a bug
somewhere downstream.

✅ **Good — Both sides of the API define the data shape independently, and they match.**
`FinancialMovement` exists as a TypeScript interface in
`financial-types.ts` and as a Pydantic model in `routes.py`. Both are
used correctly on their own side.

⚠️ **Risky — But nothing enforces that those two definitions stay matched.**
They're maintained by hand, in two different languages, with no shared
source of truth and no check that catches drift. If someone updates
one side and forgets the other, nothing will flag it — it'll just be
wrong.

## Testing

⚠️ **Risky — Business logic is tested; the UI isn't.**
`financial-utils.test.ts` and `backend/tests/test_routes.py` both
exist and cover real logic, but none of the five dashboard components
(`kpi-card`, `kpi-row`, `dashboard-header`, `income-outcome-chart`,
`profit-percent-chart`) have any test coverage. Confirmed with
`find components -name "*.test.*"` — no results. The part of the app
users actually interact with is the least protected part.

## Dependency Management & Developer Experience

✅ **Good — The dev environment supports attaching a live debugger.**
`docker-compose.yml` exposes port 5678 alongside the API port, and
`debugpy` is installed, so a developer can attach a debugger to the
backend while it's running in the container. That's a real convenience
for local development.

⚠️ **Risky — But dev and runtime dependencies aren't separated at all.**
`requirements.txt` lists `fastapi`, `uvicorn`, `debugpy`, `pytest`, and
others in one flat list, with no version pins. This is really the same
issue as the debugger above, from the other angle: the debugging setup
itself is fine, but there's no boundary anywhere between "needed to
run this" and "only needed while developing."

## Security & Configuration

✅ **Good — CORS is configured deliberately, not left to defaults.**
`main.py` sets `CORSMiddleware` explicitly rather than skipping it,
which at least means it was a conscious decision, not an oversight.

⚠️ **Risky — But it's configured wide open.**
`allow_origins=["*"]` means any origin can call this API from a
browser — combined with `allow_credentials=True`, which is a
combination generally flagged as unsafe once credentials are in play.
Not a problem for a local class project, but exactly the kind of
setting that needs tightening before this ever left `localhost`.

## Code Hygiene & Correctness

⚠️ **Risky — Dead code left in the repo.**
`frontend/src/lib/mock-data.ts` (73 lines, a `mockMovements` array) is
never imported anywhere. Confirmed by grepping for both the filename
and the exported symbol — the only match is its own declaration.

⚠️ **Risky — A hardcoded label that doesn't match the real data.**
`App.tsx` renders the header as the literal string `"2024 - Full Year"`,
but the backend generates a rolling 12-month window based on the
current date. Running the app makes this obvious: the header says
"2024," the charts show Aug 2025 → Jun 2026. This one only showed up
by actually running the app — reading the code alone wouldn't have
caught it.

---

## Summary

- **5 good practices** found, spanning API design, type safety, and
  developer tooling.
- **6 risky practices** found (one over the minimum), spanning
  architecture, type safety, testing, dependency management, security,
  and correctness.
- Two risky findings (dependency separation, the CORS wildcard) and
  one good finding (the matched-but-unenforced type contracts) point
  to the same underlying gap: there's no clear boundary anywhere in
  this repo between "fine for local dev" and "should be locked down."
  That's the clearest candidate for an actual rule in Phase 3.